{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Early programmers wrote code like a giant to‑do list. Every detail lived in one place, tangled like headphone wires in a pocket. One wrong tug, and the whole thing broke.",
      "title": "When Code Was One Big Mess"
    },
    {
      "text": "As programs grew, this spaghetti style cracked. Fixing one feature often broke five others. Developers felt like chefs trying to cook a feast in a single, overcrowded pot.",
      "title": "Growing Chaos"
    },
    {
      "text": "People tried grouping functions or organizing files, but it was like tidying a room by shoving everything under the bed. It looked better—until you needed something.",
      "title": "Failed Attempts at Order"
    },
    {
      "text": "Then came a bold idea: what if code acted like real‑world things? Little bundles that held their own data and behavior, like tiny machines you could trust to do their jobs.",
      "title": "A Radical New Lens"
    },
    {
      "text": "Objects turned programs into neighborhoods instead of mazes. Each object had its own house, its own rules, and didn’t mess with others. Suddenly, software felt manageable.",
      "title": "The Power of Encapsulation"
    },
    {
      "text": "When objects could share traits—like a bike, car, and bus all being vehicles—developers built faster. Reuse replaced repetition, like having one recipe that works for many dishes.",
      "title": "Reusing Ideas Through Inheritance"
    },
    {
      "text": "And with the magic of polymorphism, one command could work on many objects, the way saying “play” works for instruments from guitars to pianos.",
      "title": "One Idea, Many Behaviors"
    },
    {
      "text": "Today, OOP shapes apps, games, and systems everywhere. It helps teams build big ideas without drowning in complexity, turning wild software jungles into well‑kept gardens.",
      "title": "Why It Matters Now"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Imagine trying to track a speeding arrow with only snapshots. For centuries, motion looked like a flipbook with missing pages—people could see things move but couldn’t describe the “in‑between.”",
      "title": "A World Frozen in Frames"
    },
    {
      "text": "Ancient thinkers could measure distance and angles, but ask them how fast something was moving at an exact moment, and everything fell apart—like trying to bake without knowing the heat of the oven.",
      "title": "The Missing Ingredient"
    },
    {
      "text": "Mathematicians tried clever tricks—chopping shapes into pieces, guessing slopes, stretching geometry until it creaked. But their tools were like dull knives: useful, but never sharp enough.",
      "title": "Tools That Almost Worked"
    },
    {
      "text": "Then came a bold idea: what if you zoomed in so close that the messy, curvy world looked straight and simple for a split second? Newton and Leibniz realized this tiny view unlocked the secrets of change.",
      "title": "The Mind‑Bending Zoom"
    },
    {
      "text": "Suddenly, falling apples, spinning planets, and flowing rivers could be described with precision. The universe wasn’t chaos—it had a rhythm you could write down.",
      "title": "When the World Became Predictable"
    },
    {
      "text": "Today, every animation you watch, every bridge you cross, every medical model you rely on owes its existence to this language of change that began with a simple question: what happens in the tiniest moment?",
      "title": "Why It Still Shapes Our World"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Picture a world where every creature was thought to be a fixed design, like figurines on a shelf—unchanged since creation, no matter how harsh the environment shifted around them.",
      "title": "Before Change Existed"
    },
    {
      "text": "Farmers noticed tiny quirks—stronger sheep, sweeter apples—but no one imagined these small differences could rewrite the future of a species.",
      "title": "Hints in Plain Sight"
    },
    {
      "text": "Then a curious young naturalist boarded a ship. Darwin wasn’t chasing fame; he was chasing oddities—strange birds, giant tortoises, patterns that felt like nature whispering clues.",
      "title": "Darwin Sets Sail"
    },
    {
      "text": "On the Galápagos, he saw animals that looked like cousins, not twins. It was like viewing nature’s rough drafts scattered across islands.",
      "title": "Islands of Clues"
    },
    {
      "text": "Back home, Darwin pieced the puzzle together. What if life wasn’t static? What if nature quietly “selected” the traits that helped creatures survive, like a coach choosing the best players?",
      "title": "The Big Insight"
    },
    {
      "text": "The idea shook the world. Suddenly, every feather, claw, and leaf told a story of struggle and survival—of species sculpted by time.",
      "title": "A Revolutionary Shift"
    },
    {
      "text": "Today, evolution explains everything from antibiotic resistance to the diversity of life around us. It’s the backstage pass to life’s ongoing performance.",
      "title": "Why It Still Matters"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Picture ancient marketplaces where debates raged like street music. People argued about everything, yet no one agreed on what counted as a “good” argument. It was like playing a game with no rules.",
      "title": "A World of Wild Debates"
    },
    {
      "text": "Without shared rules, clever talkers could twist words like circus performers. Truth felt slippery, and persuasion often beat clarity. People longed for something steadier.",
      "title": "The Trouble with Talk"
    },
    {
      "text": "Early thinkers tried simple tricks—spotting contradictions or avoiding emotional traps—but it was patchy, like fixing a leaky roof with tape. Nothing felt universal.",
      "title": "Patchwork Solutions"
    },
    {
      "text": "Then philosophers like Aristotle asked a bold question: what if thinking itself had hidden patterns, like notes in music? Find the pattern, and you find the truth beneath the noise.",
      "title": "A Radical Insight"
    },
    {
      "text": "Suddenly, arguments could be tested, not just felt. Logic became a compass—a tool that pointed toward sound reasoning, no matter who held it.",
      "title": "Reason Gets Its Compass"
    },
    {
      "text": "Today, logic shapes everything from courtroom arguments to computer code. It's the backbone of clear thinking, helping us cut through confusion in a noisy world.",
      "title": "Why It Still Matters"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Imagine viver num mundo onde uma moeda comprava o mesmo por décadas. Era como usar o mesmo ingresso de cinema para sempre. Mas esse mundo começou a mudar quando a economia ficou mais movimentada.",
      "title": "Quando o preço quase não mudava"
    },
    {
      "text": "Com mais gente comprando e vendendo, surgiu um aperto: muitos querendo produtos, poucos produtos disponíveis. Era como disputar o último pedaço de bolo numa festa lotada.",
      "title": "A fila que cresceu demais"
    },
    {
      "text": "Governos tentaram resolver imprimindo mais dinheiro. Parecia mágica: mais notas, mais riqueza. Mas logo perceberam que era como diluir suco demais — quanto mais água, menos sabor.",
      "title": "A tentação de criar dinheiro"
    },
    {
      "text": "Quando mais dinheiro circula do que coisas para comprar, os preços começam a subir. De repente, o carrinho do mercado parecia ficar mais leve enquanto a conta ficava pesada.",
      "title": "O momento do estouro"
    },
    {
      "text": "Com o tempo, inflação virou um termômetro da economia. Mostra se estamos vivendo calmaria ou turbulência. Hoje, entender inflação é como saber ler a previsão do tempo do seu bolso.",
      "title": "Por que isso importa hoje"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Imagina vivir en un mundo donde las cosas caen, los planetas se mueven y nadie puede explicar por qué. Era como caminar bajo un techo que gotea sin saber de dónde viene el agua.",
      "title": "Un mundo sin explicación"
    },
    {
      "text": "Las civilizaciones antiguas veían caer una manzana igual que tú, pero lo explicaban con dioses caprichosos. El cielo era un rompecabezas que parecían no poder armar.",
      "title": "Culpando a los dioses"
    },
    {
      "text": "Los griegos intentaron razonar: ¿caen porque buscan su “lugar natural”? Era una idea elegante, pero no respondía por qué la Luna no caía ni se escapaba.",
      "title": "La hipótesis del “lugar”"
    },
    {
      "text": "Durante siglos, el cielo y la Tierra eran dos mundos separados. Lo que caía aquí no tenía nada que ver con lo que brillaba allá arriba… o eso creían.",
      "title": "Dos mundos divididos"
    },
    {
      "text": "Entonces llegó una época de curiosidad feroz. Galileo dejó caer objetos desde torres y descubrió que no obedecían las reglas antiguas. La gravedad empezaba a hablar.",
      "title": "Galileo escucha la caída"
    },
    {
      "text": "Un día, Newton se preguntó algo simple: ¿y si la manzana y la Luna obedecen la misma fuerza? Como unir dos piezas de un rompecabezas ignorado por siglos.",
      "title": "La chispa de Newton"
    },
    {
      "text": "Su idea fue revolucionaria: una sola fuerza invisible tiraba de todo, desde una piedra hasta los planetas. Por fin, el cielo y la Tierra hablaban el mismo idioma.",
      "title": "Una fuerza para unirlos"
    },
    {
      "text": "Gracias a esta revelación, pudimos predecir órbitas, lanzar satélites y entender por qué no flotamos. La gravedad dejó de ser un misterio y se volvió una herramienta.",
      "title": "El orden del cosmos"
    },
    {
      "text": "Cada vez que ves caer un objeto o miras la Luna, estás presenciando la misma fuerza que Newton imaginó. Entenderla es leer el guion oculto del universo.",
      "title": "Por qué te importa hoy"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "For decades, computers treated language like a puzzle of symbols. They didn’t “read”—they just matched patterns, like a tourist memorizing phrases without knowing what they meant.",
      "title": "When Words Were Just Symbols"
    },
    {
      "text": "Early chatbots felt like talking to an answering machine. Ask something slightly off-script, and they froze. Language was messy, and rules couldn’t keep up.",
      "title": "The Limits of Rules"
    },
    {
      "text": "Researchers tried stuffing machines with dictionaries and grammar books. But it was like teaching someone to cook only through recipes—no intuition, no taste.",
      "title": "When Knowledge Fell Short"
    },
    {
      "text": "The turning point came when scientists realized language is learned by experience. Feed machines mountains of real text, and patterns start to emerge naturally.",
      "title": "The Data Awakening"
    },
    {
      "text": "Neural networks began spotting connections the way our brains do—seeing meaning not in single words, but in how words dance together.",
      "title": "A New Way to Learn"
    },
    {
      "text": "Transformers supercharged this shift. Instead of reading one word at a time, they took in whole passages, noticing subtle relationships like a conductor sensing an orchestra’s rhythm.",
      "title": "Enter the Transformer"
    },
    {
      "text": "Suddenly, models could write stories, explain jokes, and even summarize arguments. It felt less like programming and more like conversation.",
      "title": "When Machines Found Their Voice"
    },
    {
      "text": "Today, LLMs help us draft emails, translate ideas, and brainstorm creatively. They matter because they make computers feel less like tools and more like collaborators.",
      "title": "Why It Matters Now"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Before set theory, math felt like a messy desk. Everyone talked about “collections” of numbers or shapes, but no one agreed on the rules. It worked—mostly—until deeper questions started piling up.",
      "title": "A Messy Mathematical Desk"
    },
    {
      "text": "As math grew, people combined ideas like puzzle pieces… except sometimes the pieces didn’t quite fit. Paradoxes popped up like loose screws in a machine that had been running too fast.",
      "title": "When Problems Started Creaking"
    },
    {
      "text": "Early attempts tried patching the leaks—define this here, fix that there. But it was like taping a cracked water pipe; every fix created a new drip somewhere else.",
      "title": "Patching the Cracks"
    },
    {
      "text": "Then came the bold idea: what if we build the rules for collections from the ground up? Start simple. Be precise. No assumptions. It was the mathematical version of finally reading the manual.",
      "title": "A Radical Reset"
    },
    {
      "text": "Set theory became the clean countertop under every modern math recipe. Functions, sequences, probability—each rests on the simple idea of well‑defined sets playing by clear rules.",
      "title": "A New Foundation Appears"
    },
    {
      "text": "Today, set theory is the quiet engine behind discrete math. It gives you a reliable toolkit for talking about objects, groups, and structures without the chaos of guesswork.",
      "title": "Why It Still Matters"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Picture early computers like giant filing cabinets. If you needed a piece of information, you had to dig through piles of digital papers one by one. Slow, messy, and easy to break.",
      "title": "Before Order Existed"
    },
    {
      "text": "As data grew, the chaos grew with it. Businesses drowned in information—orders, records, inventory—scattered across fragile files that crashed if you looked at them wrong.",
      "title": "The Rising Chaos"
    },
    {
      "text": "People tried patching solutions: custom scripts, giant spreadsheets, home‑built file systems. They worked, kind of—like fixing a sinking boat with tape.",
      "title": "Desperate Workarounds"
    },
    {
      "text": "Then came a revolutionary idea: what if data could live in structured ‘containers’ that knew how to organize themselves and answer questions fast?",
      "title": "A Radical Insight"
    },
    {
      "text": "Early databases appeared, but the real shift came when researchers imagined data like a city grid—rows, columns, addresses—easy to navigate and endlessly expandable.",
      "title": "The City Map Moment"
    },
    {
      "text": "Suddenly, computers could find information in milliseconds. Data snapped into place, relationships made sense, and whole industries unlocked new speed and reliability.",
      "title": "Order From the Chaos"
    },
    {
      "text": "Today, every app you open leans on this breakthrough—from playlists to bank accounts. Databases quietly power the world by keeping our digital lives organized.",
      "title": "Why It Still Matters"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Picture artists chained to tradition, forced to paint stiff heroes inside dim studios. The rules were so strict it felt like painting inside a tiny box with no air.",
      "title": "Before the Rebellion"
    },
    {
      "text": "Artists longed to paint real life—breezes, crowded cafés, sunlight dancing on water. But critics demanded perfection, not the messy beauty of the everyday.",
      "title": "A Craving for Freedom"
    },
    {
      "text": "Some dared to step outside, literally. They grabbed their gear, chased sunlight, and painted on the spot. But their quick strokes looked strange to the art establishment.",
      "title": "Breaking Out of the Studio"
    },
    {
      "text": "When their work was mocked as mere 'impressions,' the painters embraced the insult. It was like wearing a nickname meant to embarrass you—only you make it iconic.",
      "title": "An Insult Turned Identity"
    },
    {
      "text": "Their loose brushwork captured fleeting moments the way a photo captures a blink. Viewers could feel the morning chill, the river’s sparkle, the heartbeat of Paris.",
      "title": "Catching Life Mid‑Blink"
    },
    {
      "text": "Soon, the art world cracked open. If light could be painted freely, what else could be? Impressionism turned art into an exploration, not an exam.",
      "title": "A Door Swings Open"
    },
    {
      "text": "Today, every snapshot‑like painting, every bold experiment with color and light, traces back to those rebels who dared to see the world as it shimmered in the moment.",
      "title": "Why It Still Matters"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Antes, tentar entender a sociedade era como observar um quebra‑cabeça sem a foto da caixa. Cada pensador via um pedaço diferente, mas ninguém enxergava o todo.",
      "title": "Um mundo sem mapa social"
    },
    {
      "text": "Com revoluções, cidades lotadas e novas formas de trabalho, tudo mudou rápido demais. As velhas explicações não davam conta do caos que surgia.",
      "title": "A vida virou um redemoinho"
    },
    {
      "text": "Filósofos tentavam adivinhar as causas dos problemas sociais, mas era como tentar prever o clima olhando só pela janela: faltavam métodos, dados, rigor.",
      "title": "Tentativas que não bastavam"
    },
    {
      "text": "A virada veio quando alguns pensadores decidiram estudar a sociedade como se estuda um laboratório: observar, comparar, buscar padrões. Nascia uma ciência.",
      "title": "O estalo científico"
    },
    {
      "text": "Comte, Durkheim e Marx transformaram perguntas soltas em investigações sistemáticas. Eles deram ferramentas para enxergar além do óbvio e entender as forças invisíveis do social.",
      "title": "Os arquitetos do olhar social"
    },
    {
      "text": "Hoje, a Sociologia nos ajuda a decifrar por que grupos entram em conflito, como surgem normas e por que mudamos juntos. É como ganhar óculos que revelam o que estava escondido.",
      "title": "Por que isso importa agora"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Before computers, people solved big problems by breaking them into chunks—like cleaning a messy room corner by corner. But some tasks felt like staring at a maze with no obvious path through.",
      "title": "Before the Maze Had a Map"
    },
    {
      "text": "Think of puzzles like navigating family trees or splitting a pizza endlessly. People knew the pattern repeated, but there wasn’t a clean way to let the solution mirror itself.",
      "title": "Patterns Begging to Repeat"
    },
    {
      "text": "Early programmers tried long, clunky code to handle repetitive structures. It worked, but felt like writing pages of instructions just to open a set of nested boxes.",
      "title": "The Clunky Workarounds"
    },
    {
      "text": "Then came the bold idea: what if a function could call itself the way you ask a mirror what you look like? Suddenly, code could follow nature’s loops instead of fighting them.",
      "title": "The Mirror Moment"
    },
    {
      "text": "With recursion, complex tasks—sorting lists, exploring trees, solving puzzles—became elegant. Like giving the computer a single rule and letting it echo down the tunnel until the job is done.",
      "title": "Echoes That Solve Problems"
    },
    {
      "text": "Today, recursion shapes everything from file systems to AI search. Understanding it isn’t just learning a trick—it’s learning to think in loops nature already uses.",
      "title": "Why It Still Matters"
    }
  ]
}
